00:26:33,092 --> 00:26:35,186
Okay. We go with
Foreman's tularemia.

454
00:26:35,260 --> 00:26:39,391
Start her on I.V. chloramphenicol, 25
milligrams per kilogram, four times a day.

455
00:26:39,465 --> 00:26:41,457
Good night.

456
00:26:53,946 --> 00:26:57,576
Where's Ed? Right next to you.

457
00:26:57,649 --> 00:26:59,811
Well, you're two
down, two to go.

458
00:27:01,920 --> 00:27:03,855
Two days?

459
00:27:03,922 --> 00:27:07,689
No. Doses. You have about
20 more days of this fun.

460
00:27:07,759 --> 00:27:10,422
What time is it?

461
00:27:10,496 --> 00:27:14,331
About 4:00 a.m. I
pulled the short straw.

462
00:27:17,569 --> 00:27:19,561
Flow rate looks good.

463
00:27:24,443 --> 00:27:26,435
No rash or flushing.

464
00:27:27,446 --> 00:27:30,075
What time is it?

465
00:27:31,416 --> 00:27:33,976
4:00 a.m.

466
00:27:34,052 --> 00:27:36,453
Do you not remember just asking?

467
00:27:38,724 --> 00:27:40,716
I don't...

468
00:27:40,792 --> 00:27:43,057
Elyse?

469
00:27:44,930 --> 00:27:47,866
Elyse? Elyse?

470
00:27:47,933 --> 00:27:50,767
- Elyse.
- What are you doing?

471
00:27:50,836 --> 00:27:52,862
- I'm trying to wake her.
- She fall asleep again?

472
00:27:52,938 --> 00:27:55,203
In the middle of a
sentence. Elyse. Elyse.

473
00:27:55,274 --> 00:27:58,836
<i>- What's happening?</i>
- Patient's not responding.

474
00:27:58,911 --> 00:28:01,176
Pulse is fine. Airway's open.

475
00:28:01,246 --> 00:28:03,238
Check her blood pressure.

476
00:28:04,850 --> 00:28:07,115
Pupils are reactive.

477
00:28:07,186 --> 00:28:09,781
Elyse, wake up.
You gotta wake up.

478
00:28:09,855 --> 00:28:13,656
- What does that mean? What are you doing?
- She's unresponsive to pain.

479
00:28:13,725 --> 00:28:16,627
<i>Come on, Elyse.</i>

480
00:28:16,695 --> 00:28:19,927
- Is she dying?
- I don't know.

481
00:28:30,375 --> 00:28:32,241
She's in a coma.

482
00:28:38,684 --> 00:28:42,246
<i>There's only one way a tularemia
patient goes into a coma...</i>

483
00:28:42,321 --> 00:28:44,256
while on I.V. chloramphenicol.

484
00:28:44,323 --> 00:28:47,657
The patient doesn't have
tularemia. And then there was one.

485
00:28:47,726 --> 00:28:49,752
Patient comes in 'cause
she's sleeping too much.

486
00:28:49,828 --> 00:28:51,862
It takes 10 doctors
and a coma to diagnose

487
00:28:51,886 --> 00:28:53,993
sleeping sickness. And
then there was none.

488
00:28:54,066 --> 00:28:57,127
We still have the problem of explaining
how a white chick from Jersey...

489
00:28:57,202 --> 00:28:59,762
who's never traveled south of
D.C. has African sleeping sickness.

490
00:28:59,805 --> 00:29:02,036
Still have the
obvious explanation.

491
00:29:03,041 --> 00:29:05,370
I made it clear. If
this guy's lying about

492
00:29:05,394 --> 00:29:08,139
sleeping around he knows
he's murdering his wife.

493
00:29:08,213 --> 00:29:10,375
Does seem unlikely.

494
00:29:10,449 --> 00:29:12,441
Go away.

495
00:29:29,735 --> 00:29:32,102
<i>What are you doing?</i>

496
00:29:33,305 --> 00:29:35,706
Checking for lymphadenopathy.

497
00:29:35,774 --> 00:29:39,404
And waiting for
you. Who are you?

498
00:29:39,478 --> 00:29:41,572
I'm Dr. House.

499
00:29:41,647 --> 00:29:44,617
Your wife has human
African trypanosomiasis.

500
00:29:46,118 --> 00:29:49,452
Sleeping sickness. You
mean it's not tularemia,

501
00:29:49,521 --> 00:29:52,081
a virus, tumor or—or cancer?

502
00:29:52,157 --> 00:29:55,025
No.

503
00:29:56,728 --> 00:29:58,856
I've never had an affair.

504
00:29:58,930 --> 00:30:01,024
I believe you.

505
00:30:01,099 --> 00:30:03,694
And I trust Elyse.

506
00:30:05,470 --> 00:30:09,237
The treatment for this
disease is a drug that's...

507
00:30:09,308 --> 00:30:12,301
fatal on its own
10% of the time.

508
00:30:12,377 --> 00:30:16,439
Which is why I need your written
consent before I can legally prescribe it.

509
00:30:16,515 --> 00:30:20,077
Why would she lie if she knew it could
kill her? I don't ask why patients lie.

510
00:30:20,152 --> 00:30:22,087
I just assume they all do.

511
00:30:22,154 --> 00:30:24,749
But why? To protect you,

512
00:30:24,823 --> 00:30:27,884
because she didn't think it mattered,
it just seemed easier, because...

513
00:30:29,428 --> 00:30:31,420
that's what people do.

514
00:30:34,266 --> 00:30:37,828
If you're absolutely certain that your wife
has never had sex with anyone but you...

515
00:30:37,903 --> 00:30:40,429
since you were
married, then I'm wrong.

516
00:30:42,207 --> 00:30:46,702
But if you think there's a
possibility that just one time...

517
00:30:48,013 --> 00:30:50,676
she wasn't perfect...

518
00:30:50,749 --> 00:30:52,911
<i>One weekend you’re out of town,</i>

519
00:30:53,919 --> 00:30:56,115
<i>one fight where
she ran to a friend,</i>

520
00:30:56,188 --> 00:30:58,248
one stupid Christmas party...

521
00:31:00,959 --> 00:31:04,054
Then you need to allow
me to start treatment.

522
00:31:05,597 --> 00:31:07,725
Because if we don't,

523
00:31:07,799 --> 00:31:09,768
she's gonna be dead
by tomorrow morning.

524
00:31:19,177 --> 00:31:21,339
You trust your wife that much?

525
00:31:23,615 --> 00:31:25,607
I don't know.

526
00:31:29,221 --> 00:31:32,316
I'm gonna start the treatment.

527
00:31:47,305 --> 00:31:51,265
Glass syringes? And
special I.V. tubing.

528
00:31:51,343 --> 00:31:54,370
Why do we need this stuff?
Because melarsoprol melts plastic.

529
00:31:54,446 --> 00:31:56,972
This stuff's basically
arsenic mixed with antifreeze.

530
00:31:58,083 --> 00:32:00,143
What doesn't kill us
makes us stronger, huh?

531
00:32:00,218 --> 00:32:03,188
Nietzsche wouldn't have been so
glib if he'd been prescribed melarsoprol.

532
00:32:05,323 --> 00:32:08,020
"Can cause vomiting,
abdominal pain,

533
00:32:08,093 --> 00:32:10,858
blood toxicity, neural
damage, cardiac arrhythmia."

534
00:32:10,929 --> 00:32:13,524
They forgot to say it's
gonna hurt like all hell.

535
00:32:13,598 --> 00:32:16,158
She's lucky she's in a coma.

536
00:32:33,118 --> 00:32:36,555
How long before we know if
it's working? It's tough to say.

537
00:32:36,621 --> 00:32:39,420
It's a good sign that she
hasn't gotten any worse.

538
00:32:42,327 --> 00:32:44,455
Does she even know I'm here?

539
00:32:44,529 --> 00:32:47,192
She knows you're
always there for her.

540
00:32:50,068 --> 00:32:52,230
Yeah.

541
00:32:52,304 --> 00:32:54,535
If she gets better,

542
00:32:54,606 --> 00:32:56,632
it means she wasn't
always there for me.

543
00:33:00,278 --> 00:33:02,804
It means she made a mistake.

544
00:33:04,316 --> 00:33:06,308
I can't help it.

545
00:33:06,384 --> 00:33:10,913
Part of me—a big part
of me— Can't handle that.

546
00:33:12,724 --> 00:33:15,250
It doesn't want
her to get better.

547
00:33:25,070 --> 00:33:27,062
Does that make
me a terrible person?

548
00:33:35,780 --> 00:33:37,772
Yes.

549
00:33:59,304 --> 00:34:02,001
So you're treating her for
African sleeping sickness...

550
00:34:02,073 --> 00:34:05,532
because you don't think it's possible for
someone to be faithful in a relationship?

551
00:34:05,610 --> 00:34:07,579
And you do? Yes.

552
00:34:07,646 --> 00:34:11,845
And you need to tell me that.
Look. I am not having an affair.

553
00:34:11,917 --> 00:34:15,376
I had lunch with someone
I work with—at work. Once.

554
00:34:15,453 --> 00:34:19,049
I believe you. What I don't
believe is it'll be just once.

555
00:34:19,124 --> 00:34:21,616
I love my wife. You
certainly love saying it.

556
00:34:21,693 --> 00:34:25,357
I'm sorry. I know
you love your wife.

557
00:34:25,430 --> 00:34:27,490
You loved all your
wives. Probably still do.

558
00:34:27,566 --> 00:34:30,934
In fact, you probably love all the
women you loved who weren't your wife.

559
00:34:31,002 --> 00:34:34,461
You can be a real jerk sometimes, you
know that? Yeah. And you're the good guy.

560
00:34:34,539 --> 00:34:38,135
At least I try. As long as you're trying to
be good, you can do whatever you want.

561
00:34:38,209 --> 00:34:40,155
And as long as you're
not trying, you can say

562
00:34:40,179 --> 00:34:42,544
whatever you want. So,
between us, we can do anything.

563
00:34:42,614 --> 00:34:45,140
We can rule the world.

564
00:34:57,462 --> 00:34:59,624
Mixing up some margaritas?

565
00:34:59,698 --> 00:35:01,860
Mine's a double, senorita.

566
00:35:01,933 --> 00:35:04,198
That's Portuguese,
you know. Spanish.

567
00:35:05,270 --> 00:35:07,205
Uh-oh.

568
00:35:08,473 --> 00:35:10,374
What's goin' on?

569
00:35:10,442 --> 00:35:13,207
I'm recalibrating
the centrifuge.

570
00:35:13,278 --> 00:35:15,270
Turn around.

571
00:35:24,589 --> 00:35:26,649
It's a very sad thing.

572
00:35:26,725 --> 00:35:28,694
An uncalibrated centrifuge.

573
00:35:28,760 --> 00:35:32,595
Makes me cry
too. I'm not crying.

574
00:35:33,765 --> 00:35:35,757
Okay.

575
00:35:49,114 --> 00:35:51,674
I told the husband
he was a jerk.

576
00:35:53,551 --> 00:35:55,543
Why?

577
00:36:01,693 --> 00:36:03,958
When I was in college, I...

578
00:36:06,831 --> 00:36:11,394
I fell in love,
and I got married.

579
00:36:11,469 --> 00:36:13,631
And...

580
00:36:13,705 --> 00:36:15,799
At that age, the chances
of marriage lasting...

581
00:36:15,874 --> 00:36:18,275
<i>It lasted six months.</i>

582
00:36:20,412 --> 00:36:23,576
Thyroid cancer
metastasized to his brain.

583
00:36:23,648 --> 00:36:25,742
There was nothing they could do.

584
00:36:27,852 --> 00:36:29,787
I was 21, and...

585
00:36:31,222 --> 00:36:33,157
I watched my husband die.

586
00:36:36,828 --> 00:36:38,797
I'm sorry.

587
00:36:42,967 --> 00:36:44,959
But that's not the whole story.

588
00:36:47,338 --> 00:36:50,001
It's a symptom,
not your illness.

589
00:36:50,075 --> 00:36:53,739
Thyroid cancer would have been
diagnosed at least a year before his death.

590
00:36:53,812 --> 00:36:56,304
You knew he was dying
when you married him.

591
00:36:56,381 --> 00:36:59,180
It must have been
when you first met him.

592
00:37:02,554 --> 00:37:05,524
And you married him anyway.

593
00:37:07,225 --> 00:37:11,128
You can't be that good a
person <i>and</i> well-adjusted.

594
00:37:12,330 --> 00:37:15,027
Why?

595
00:37:15,100 --> 00:37:18,093
'Cause you wind up
crying over centrifuges.

596
00:37:20,972 --> 00:37:23,635
Or hating people?

597
00:37:38,623 --> 00:37:40,558
<i>Her fever spiked at 104.</i>

598
00:37:40,625 --> 00:37:42,560
Echo shows global hyperkinesis.

599
00:37:42,627 --> 00:37:44,619
Blood pressure?
Barely 90 over 40.

600
00:37:44,696 --> 00:37:48,599
Did you give her dopamine? Started
270 micrograms per minute 10 minutes ago.

601
00:37:48,666 --> 00:37:50,965
Still no change.

602
00:37:56,474 --> 00:38:00,570
Killing the parasites isn't gonna do much
good if we kill her heart at the same time.

603
00:38:00,645 --> 00:38:03,046
A heart can be
replaced. A brain can't.

604
00:38:03,114 --> 00:38:05,413
Right now we're killing both.

605
00:38:05,483 --> 00:38:07,962
If she's gonna die, we
should at least let her do

606
00:38:07,986 --> 00:38:10,387
it without that acid
flowing through her veins.

607
00:38:10,455 --> 00:38:12,947
What's happening?

608
00:38:14,192 --> 00:38:18,755
We would've expected your wife's
condition to show some improvement by now.

609
00:38:18,830 --> 00:38:20,765
It hasn't.

610
00:38:20,832 --> 00:38:22,824
It's going the other way.

611
00:38:53,965 --> 00:38:55,957
Please don't die.

612
00:38:57,869 --> 00:38:59,861
Please don't die.

613
00:39:24,996 --> 00:39:26,828
She's awake.

614
00:40:07,872 --> 00:40:10,774
Hey. She's gonna be okay.

615
00:40:10,842 --> 00:40:13,641
Yeah. Sure.

616
00:40:41,572 --> 00:40:44,406
What are you gonna do?

617
00:40:44,475 --> 00:40:47,001
Were you always honest with her?

618
00:40:47,078 --> 00:40:50,845
Do you know how lucky you are?
Your wife is alive. She loves you.

619
00:40:50,915 --> 00:40:53,885
What she did...

620
00:40:53,952 --> 00:40:56,854
You can't love a person
and do that to them.

621
00:40:59,557 --> 00:41:02,083
She loves you.

622
00:41:38,663 --> 00:41:41,360
I need to know who
you had the affair with.

623
00:41:45,003 --> 00:41:47,837
He has to be notified so
he can get treatment as well.

624
00:41:52,176 --> 00:41:54,509
Why did you lie to us?

625
00:41:54,579 --> 00:41:57,071
You knew your life was at stake.

626
00:42:03,488 --> 00:42:05,889
He's not coming back, is he?

627
00:42:10,695 --> 00:42:12,926
We all make mistakes,

628
00:42:12,997 --> 00:42:14,966
and we all pay a price.

629
00:42:23,708 --> 00:42:26,041
I need that name.

630
00:42:39,824 --> 00:42:42,020
Hey, there. How you doin'?

631
00:42:42,093 --> 00:42:44,028
Fine.

632
00:42:45,897 --> 00:42:47,866
Do you know where your dad is?

633
00:42:57,341 --> 00:42:59,333
Can I help you?

634
00:43:49,060 --> 00:43:50,323
That's some bad hat, Harry.
